result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (5th or 6th) and Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (5th or 6th) was dismissed by the court.

  • Claressa S Regner was found guilty of OWI (5th or 6th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

[MK] case called at 1:46pm. 
Defendant Claressa S Regner in court with Attorney Jeffrey J De La Rosa.  ADA Monica Hall appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
[Clerk's added note: The Defendant is not in custody. Court staff has learned that Ms. Regner was released on electronic monitoring from the Waukesha Jail on July 20th, despite the Court having revoked Bond in this case.]
Sentencing arguments given by counsel. 
Ms. Regner makes a statement. 

On Count # 1, the Court sentences Ms. Regner to 3 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 2 years, and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 1 year.  This sentence is to commence forthwith. 
The Court finds that Ms. Regner is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program "Boot Camp".
The Court finds that Ms. Regner is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.
The Court gives 40 days credit for time already served.

The Court orders as conditions of Extended Supervision:
-- those conditions as determined by the Department of Corrections
--to pay a $600 fine plus costs and surcharges including that Ms. Regner is to pay the $56.74 blood testing cost incurred by the Lake Mills Police Department
--Ms. Regner is to comply with DNA sample provision.

The Court orders outright:  
--revocation of operating privileges for 36 months commencing forthwith 
--six demerit points are assessed 
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through  
--Ignition Interlock Device requirement/restrictions for 36 months 

The Court indicates that it is not ordering attendance at a Victim Impact Panel.

[MK] case called at 1:18pm. 
Defendant Claressa S Regner appears via videoconferencing from the Jefferson County Jail, in custody, with Attorney Jeffrey De La Rosa (PD will appoint counsel).  Public Service Prosecutor Melanie Flint appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
On agreement of counsel, the Court finds that the videoconferencing system is sight and sound sufficient. 
Ms. Regner verifies that the date of birth and address on the Criminal Complaint are correct. 
Service of Complaint admitted, reading waived, the charges and maximum penalties are recited. 
Preliminary Hearing time limits are waived by both parties.

The Court requires a $1,000 Cash Bond, with conditions:
--to maintain absolute sobriety:  no possession or ingestion of alcohol
--no presence in bars, taverns, liquor stores
--no possession or ingestion of controlled substances without a valid prescription
- no operation of a motor vehicle without a valid drivers license.
-  The Defendant is to report and comply with SCRAM alcohol monitoring program as administered by Wisconsin Community Services.  The Court orders the defendant to SCRAM monitoring through WCS, with the consideration of Remote Breath as an alternative only when WCS verifies that a defendant's work environment or health condition prohibits the SCRAM bracelet.  The Defendant is to comply with all SCRAM Program conditions of participation including payment of program costs and fees.  **If in custody, release on SCRAM only.**
recess 1:24pm.
